{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656885"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:19:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:19:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18774"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18774"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11506"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78706"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11506"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64049"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10612"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26942"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78706"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring fertilisation, sperm must undergo specific changes to successfully penetrate the egg. The acrosome is a specialised structure in the sperm head containing enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the acrosome reaction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Development of sperm motility","Formation of the acrosome during spermatogenesis","Fusion of sperm and egg cell membranes","Production of energy for sperm movement","Release of hydrolytic enzymes to digest the zona pellucida"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erelease of hydrolytic enzymes to digest the zona pellucida\u003C/strong\u003E is the key function of the acrosome reaction. When sperm bind to the zona pellucida, calcium influx triggers the fusion of the acrosomal membrane with the sperm plasma membrane, releasing enzymes that help the sperm penetrate through the zona pellucida to reach the egg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of the acrosome during spermatogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs much earlier during sperm development, not during fertilisation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFusion of sperm and egg cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs after the sperm has penetrated the zona pellucida\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelopment of sperm motility\u003C/strong\u003E - Motility develops during sperm maturation in the epididymis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of energy for sperm movement\u003C/strong\u003E - Energy is produced by mitochondria in the sperm midpiece\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe acrosome reaction is an essential step in fertilisation, as it allows the sperm to penetrate the protective barriers surrounding the egg.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The acrosome reaction releases hydrolytic enzymes that help sperm penetrate the zona pellucida of the egg.","Calcium influx triggers the acrosome reaction when sperm bind to the zona pellucida.","The acrosome reaction is essential for successful fertilisation of the egg."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":